  "timeframe": "1D",
  "market_context": "Uptrend on BTCUSD daily chart following a break above a prior resistance level; analyst demonstrates how to identify swing highs and lows in real market conditions versus textbook idealized trends.",
  "key_observation": "The analyst emphasizes that a valid break of structure requires a candle close above the prior high—not just a wick—and identifies major lows as the lowest points of moves that caused structure breaks.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identify the initial low as the lowest point of the move that broke the prior structure (first upward impulsive move).",
    "Step 2: Mark the highest point of that same impulsive move as the first swing high of the uptrend.",
    "Step 3: After price pulls back, identify the next swing low as the lowest point of the move that broke the prior high (confirmed by candle close above the previous high).",
    "Step 4: Identify the next swing high as the peak of the subsequent impulsive move, noting that a wick above the prior high without close confirmation is not a valid break (liquidity grab).",
    "Step 5: Repeat the process: trace back each new high to its preceding impulsive move to locate the corresponding swing low."
  ],
  "outcome": null,
  "lessons": "In real markets, uptrends are jagged; valid structure breaks require candle closes—not wicks—and swing lows are defined by the lowest point of the move that created the break, not arbitrary local minima.",
